explanation:
For assessing whether any statements in OS_CloseAllFiles are dead (i.e. can be removed without affecting program behaviour) you must know the observable effects and control behavior of the iterator and the per-entry processing. Each listed symbol is required for that reason:

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorGetNext
  - Controls loop iteration. You must know whether it has any side effects and how/when it returns false; if it changes state or timing then removing the loop/body could change behaviour.

- OS_FileIteratorClose
  - This is the callback passed to OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry. If it performs observable actions (closing file descriptors, releasing resources, generating events, affecting timing), those are relevant to whether the call is dead.

- OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit
  - Called (indirectly via OS_ObjectIdIterateActive) to initialise the iterator. Initialization may have observable effects (allocations, transactions, timestamps); needed to determine if iterator setup/removal changes behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel
  - Called by OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy. Iterator destruction may cancel transactions or release resources; these side effects are relevant to whether removing the destroy call (or the iterator usage) alters program behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIdFromToken
  - Used by OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry to map iterator tokens to objects. It may validate/modify state or raise errors; its side effects (or lack thereof) affect whether processing each entry is required.

- OS_Lock_Global and OS_Unlock_Global
  - Called by OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry around critical sections. Locking/unlocking changes concurrency/timing and can be observable (deadlock avoidance, ordering). Even if a function appears redundant logically, its locking may be required for correct concurrent behaviour.

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The return-code constant used by the function. To determine whether setting/propagating return_code is meaningful (i.e. whether differences in return values would affect callers), you must know the actual value(s) and semantics.

Together these symbols let the analyser determine (a) whether the loop executes and why, (b) whether processing an entry produces observable effects, and (c) whether iterator init/destroy and locking are behaviourally relevant (including timing/concurrency). Without their definitions/semantics you cannot soundly conclude that any executed operation in OS_CloseAllFiles is removable (dead) per the MISRA rule.
